Task 1: Storage Method Comparison

Shared Preferences

Advantages

Simple and easy to use.
Lightweight and requires minimal resources.
Provides fast access to stored data.
Suitable for storing small key-value data such as user settings and login information.

Disadvantages

Not secure for sensitive information.
Supports only limited data types.
Not suitable for storing large amounts of data.
Cannot perform complex queries.

SQLite

Advantages

Works offline without an internet connection.
Supports structured data storage.
Allows complex queries and data retrieval.
Suitable for managing large amounts of data.
Reliable and widely used in mobile applications.

Disadvantages

Requires knowledge of SQL.
More complex to implement than Shared Preferences.
Does not support real-time synchronization.
Database management may become difficult as the application grows.

Firebase

Advantages

Provides real-time data synchronization.
Stores data in the cloud.
Easily scalable for large applications.
Allows data sharing across multiple devices.
Reduces the need for managing a backend server.

Disadvantages

Requires an internet connection for most features.
Depends heavily on Google's services.
Costs can increase as usage grows.
Less control over data management compared to local databases.

Internal Storage

Advantages

Data is private and secure within the application.
Does not require an internet connection.
Suitable for storing files such as images and documents.
Easy to access from within the application.

Disadvantages

Data cannot be easily shared with other applications.
Requires manual file management.
Not suitable for structured data storage.
Limited by the device's storage capacity.
